<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF206-954-290  </DOCNO><DOCID>06 954 290.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  Jan 16 1989 v6 n2 p55(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Channel changes at Apple. (Apple Computer Inc.) (Currents)andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT>Company:   Apple Computer Inc. (officials and employees).andO;Ticker:    AAPL.andO;Topic:     Computer industry.andO;Person:    Boesenberg, Charles (resignation, retirement, etc.).andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Channel Changes at AppleandM;Charles Boesenberg, senior vice president of sales at Apple USA, a divisionof Apple Computer Inc., is departing to join MIPS Computer Systems Inc., ofSunnyvale, Calif.andM;Boesenberg is credited with many of the successful reseller training andmarketing plans instituted by Apple in the last two years.andM;In March he will join MIPS, a privately held supplier of Reduced InstructionSet Computer technologies, as executive vice president of marketing andpresident of an unnamed business unit.andP;  According to Wall Street analysts,Boesenberg's departure is evidence of Apple USA President Allan Loren'sdesire to restructure and revamp his division.andM;Some analysts are concerned about the recent turnover of high-level positionsat Apple.andM;In the last six months, Deborah Coleman, Apple's vice president of financeand chief financial officer, announced she will be starting a five-monthleave of absence in February.andP;  In addition, Delbert Yocam, senior vicepresident and president of Apple Pacific, said he will give up hisoperational duties at the company in November 1989.andM;William Coldrick, previously vice president and general manager of NorthwestOperations at Apple USA, will replace Boesenberg as senior vice president ofsales.andP;  Godfrey Sullivan, previously Apple's director of U.S.andP;  salesdevelopment, will replace Coldrick.andM;CFA Looks to the Long TermandM;''In the long run we are all dead,'' one Wall Street analyst said of TheComputer Factory's apparent abandonment of short-term profits for long-termgrowth.andM;After attending a closed-door company meeting, Andrew Neff, of Bear, Stearnsandamp; Co., quoted economist John Maynard Keynes as he argued that the computerreseller is putting less emphasis on short-term profits in favor of long-termsuccess.andP;  Other analysts who had attended the meeting agreed.andM;''Jay Gottlieb, [the company's president], is a major stockholder, and it'sclear he's managing for the long run vs.andP;  the short run,'' said Charles Wolf,an analyst with investment bank First Boston Corp., of New York.andP;  ''The firmwants to expand into new markets, and if it has an effect on margins, then sobe it.''andM;According to analysts, Gottlieb wants the Elmsford, N.Y., firm to be in thetop 10 markets by the end of 1989.andP;  That will mean expansion into Detroit,Houston and Dallas, according to Wolf.andM;The Computer Factory's expansion into California last year and its strategicshift from retail sales to the highly competitive corporate-sales market hasreduced gross margins from 22.8 percent to 21 percent, according to KevinMcCarthy, an analyst with Mabon, Nugent andamp; Co., a New York investment bank.andO;Following The Computer Factory meeting, McCarthy lowered hisearnings-per-share estimate to $1.25, down from $1.60.andO;</TEXT></DOC>